  <worksheet xml:id="act-linear-desmos">
    <title>Linear Functions with Desmos <mdash/> Slopes and y-Intercepts</title>
    
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Use <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator" visual="desmos.com/calculator">Desmos</url> to complete the following investigation. Be ready to discuss your findings with your group and with the class.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Type <m>y = mx + b</m> into the entry line on the left side of the screen. Notice that Desmos allows you to create sliders for <m>m</m> and <m>b</m>. Do this by clicking the <q>all</q> button.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Set <m>b = 0</m>. Play with <m>m</m>. Describe the appearance of the line when:
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>m = 0</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>m \lt 0</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>m \gt 0</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What effect does changing <m>m</m> have on the graph of <m>y = mx</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Why does <m>m</m> have the effect you say it does?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Graph the line <m>y = x</m> by typing it into the next entry line on the left side of the screen.
